    <h1 class="styledH1">What Is RAM</h1>
    <hr class="h1Line"/>

    <img class="SideImages" src="../Images/RAM.png" />
    <p>
        RAM, or Random Access Memory, is a fundamental component in computer systems, serving as temporary storage for data and instructions that the CPU needs to access quickly. Unlike long-term storage devices such as hard drives or SSDs, RAM is volatile memory, meaning its contents are lost when the computer is powered off. RAM plays a crucial role in multitasking and overall system performance by providing fast access to data for the CPU. When an application is running, its data and instructions are loaded into RAM, allowing the CPU to access them rapidly for processing. The amount of RAM in a system directly impacts its multitasking capabilities and responsiveness. Additionally, the speed and latency of RAM modules influence overall system performance, particularly in tasks that involve frequent data access. Upgrading RAM can often improve a computer's performance, especially when dealing with memory-intensive applications or multitasking scenarios.
    </p>


    <h1 class="styledH1">How To Choose RAM</h1>
    <hr class="h1Line"/>

    <img class="SideImages" src="../Images/RAM2.png" />
    <p>
        When choosing RAM for your computer, it's essential to consider compatibility with your CPU, motherboard, and budget constraints. For high-performance Intel CPUs like the Core i9 series, which benefit from faster memory speeds, selecting DDR4 or DDR5 RAM modules with higher frequencies, such as 3600MHz or above, can maximize system performance. Look for RAM kits from reputable brands like Corsair, G.Skill, or Kingston, ensuring compatibility with your motherboard's chipset and CPU. For mid-range Intel CPUs like the Core i5 or i7 series, DDR4 RAM modules with speeds around 3200MHz offer a good balance of performance and affordability. Brands like Crucial, TeamGroup, and Adata provide reliable options at competitive prices. When working with budget-oriented Intel CPUs like the Core i3 or Pentium series, DDR4 RAM modules with lower speeds, typically around 2666MHz, are sufficient for most tasks while keeping costs down. Consider options from brands like Patriot, PNY, or Silicon Power for affordable yet dependable RAM kits. Ultimately, prioritize RAM compatibility with your CPU and motherboard, opt for reputable brands, and select a speed and capacity that aligns with your performance needs and budget constraints.
    </p>

